---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="visas · wanderlust"
  description="Visa notes for Indian passport holders, grouped by visa regime."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-2xl">
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-medium leading-[1.05] tracking-tight md:text-5xl">
      Visas for Indian passport.
    </h1>
  </section>

  <aside class="mx-auto mt-8 max-w-2xl border-l-2 pl-6 py-2" style="border-color: var(--color-accent)">
    <p class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest" style="color: var(--color-accent)">
      Disclaimer
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
      Visa rules change. Treat these as a starting point and verify on the
      official consulate site before you apply.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <div class="prose-trip mt-12">
    <h2 id="schengen">Schengen</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      From 3 of my own Schengen visa applications, 100% approval rate.
    </p>

    <p>
      One short-stay Schengen visa covers travel across all 29 member states.
      Apply through VFS Global. Choose the country where you'll spend the most
      nights as the issuing consulate, or the country of first entry if the
      trip begins there or nights are split evenly.
    </p>

    <h3>Countries covered</h3>

    <p>
      Austria, Belgium, Bulgaria, Croatia, Czechia, Denmark, Estonia, Finland,
      France, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Iceland, Italy, Latvia, Liechtenstein,
      Lithuania, Luxembourg, Malta, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Portugal,
      Romania, Slovakia, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland.
    </p>

    <h3>Documents</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>Valid passport, plus photocopies of the first and last pages</li>
      <li>Completed visa application form</li>
      <li>Passport-size photograph per Schengen specs (35x45mm, white background)</li>
      <li>Visa fee payment receipt</li>
      <li>Confirmed return flight tickets (Emirates and Finnair sell fully refundable fares, useful since approval isn't guaranteed)</li>
      <li>Internal travel across countries (trains, buses, intra-Schengen flights)</li>
      <li>Hotel bookings covering every night of the stay (Agoda and similar OTAs have refundable rooms)</li>
      <li>Travel insurance with 30,000 EUR medical coverage</li>
      <li>Cover letter with day-wise itinerary</li>
      <li>
        Financial proof (depends on your work situation)
        <ul>
          <li>If employed: NOC from your employer (mandatory), 3 months of payslips, ITR for the last 2 years, and your 6 months of bank statements</li>
          <li>If self-employed or running a business: business registration or GST certificate, ITR for the last 2 years, and 6 months of business and personal bank statements</li>
          <li>If not working (student, between jobs, retired, dependent): sponsorship letter, sponsor's financial proofs (as per their work situation above), and proof of your relationship to the sponsor</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Event tickets (Tomatina, Oktoberfest, a marathon) help anchor the
      "purpose of visit". Print them.
    </p>

    <p>
      A few Indian providers now sell visa-rejection insurance for around
      500 INR. Worth considering since the visa fee itself is non-refundable.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
